sect1.para:
The last potential diagnosis that needed to be assessed for was ASD. Since none of the structured interviews assess for both anxiety disorders and ASD, the Autism Diagnostic Observation Schedule-Second Edition (ADOS-2; Lord et al.,
         2012
      ) was administered to see if Louise would meet the criteria for an ASD diagnosis. Although Louise did express discomfort around social interaction and eye contact, she did not exhibit unusually restricted interests, inflexibility to change, stereotyped movements, or deficits in social-emotional reciprocity. This absence of ASD symptoms indicated that Louise’s reported difficulty with social interactions and maintaining relationships is likely better explained by the MDD and social anxiety disorder diagnoses. Scores on the self-report measures of the Beck Depression Inventory-II (Beck et al., 
         1996
      ) and Social Interaction Anxiety Scale—Short Form (SIAS-SF) further documented elevated levels of depression and social anxiety symptoms.
